/**
 * @page csc Color Space Conversion (CSC) Framework
 *
 * @brief High-performance, configurable pixel format and color space
 * conversion with Highway SIMD acceleration.
 *
 * @section csc_overview Overview
 *
 * The CSC framework converts images between any pair of pixel
 * descriptions (PixelDesc), handling differences in memory layout,
 * component ordering, bit depth, chroma subsampling, color model, and
 * transfer function.  It is the implementation behind Image::convert().
 *
 * The framework has three execution tiers:
 *
 * 1. **Fast paths** ‚Äî Hand-tuned integer-domain kernels for common
 *    broadcast conversion pairs (e.g. RGBA8 ‚Üî YUV8 4:2:2 Rec.709).
 *    These bypass the generic pipeline entirely and deliver the highest
 *    throughput (3,000‚Äì10,000+ Mpix/s at 1080p).
 *
 * 2. **SIMD generic pipeline** ‚Äî A multi-stage float-domain pipeline
 *    with Highway SIMD acceleration.  Used for conversions without a
 *    registered fast path (200‚Äì1,300 Mpix/s).
 *
 * 3. **Scalar generic pipeline** ‚Äî The same multi-stage pipeline with
 *    SIMD disabled.  Selected via the `"Path"` configuration key.
 *    Useful for debugging and as a reference implementation (100‚Äì300
 *    Mpix/s).
 *
 * @section csc_pipeline Pipeline Architecture
 *
 * The generic pipeline processes one scanline at a time through an
 * ordered chain of stages.  Stages that are not needed for a given
 * conversion are eliminated at compile time.
 *
 * @code
 * Source pixels
 *   ‚Üí Unpack (memory layout ‚Üí float SoA buffers)
 *   ‚Üí Alpha fill (if target has alpha, source does not)
 *   ‚Üí Range In (limited-range integers ‚Üí 0.0‚Äì1.0)
 *   ‚Üí YCbCr‚ÜíRGB (if source is YCbCr: matrix on encoded values)
 *   ‚Üí EOTF (remove source transfer function ‚Üí linear)
 *   ‚Üí Gamut matrix (source primaries ‚Üí target primaries, linear domain)
 *   ‚Üí OETF (apply target transfer function ‚Üí encoded)
 *   ‚Üí RGB‚ÜíYCbCr (if target is YCbCr: matrix on encoded values)
 *   ‚Üí Range Out (0.0‚Äì1.0 ‚Üí target integer range)
 *   ‚Üí Pack (float SoA buffers ‚Üí target memory layout)
 * Target pixels
 * @endcode
 *
 * The YCbCr matrix operates on gamma-encoded RGB values, not linear.
 * This matches the ITU-R specifications (BT.709, BT.601, BT.2020)
 * where the luma/chroma separation is defined on the encoded signal.
 *
 * @section csc_fastpaths Fast-Path Kernels
 *
 * Fast paths are registered at static initialization via
 * CSCRegistry::registerFastPath() and discovered automatically by
 * CSCPipeline during compilation.  Each fast path is a single function
 * that converts one scanline from source to target format, bypassing
 * all pipeline stages.
 *
 * Registered fast paths (56 total):
 *
 * | Standard | Bit Depth | Formats |
 * |----------|-----------|---------|
 * | BT.709   | 8-bit     | YUYV, UYVY, NV12, NV21, NV16, Planar 422/420 ‚Üî RGBA8 |
 * | BT.709   | 10-bit LE | UYVY, Planar 422/420, NV12, v210 ‚Üî RGBA10 LE |
 * | BT.709   | 12-bit LE | UYVY, Planar 422/420, NV12 ‚Üî RGBA12 LE |
 * | BT.601   | 8-bit     | YUYV, UYVY, NV12, Planar 420 ‚Üî RGBA8 |
 * | BT.2020  | 10-bit LE | UYVY, Planar 420 ‚Üî RGBA10 LE |
 * | BT.2020  | 12-bit LE | UYVY, Planar 420 ‚Üî RGBA12 LE |
 * | Format   | 8-bit     | BGRA‚ÜîRGBA, RGBA‚ÜîRGB |
 *
 * Fast paths use fixed-point integer arithmetic with standard
 * broadcast coefficients (e.g. BT.709: Y = 66R + 129G + 25B).  They
 * do not apply separate sRGB and Rec.709 transfer functions ‚Äî the
 * input sRGB signal is treated as Rec.709 directly.  This is standard
 * broadcast practice and produces results within ¬±1 LSB of the ITU
 * integer reference for 8-bit.
 *
 * @section csc_accuracy Accuracy Characteristics
 *
 * @par Scalar pipeline vs Color::convert()
 * The scalar generic pipeline uses the same float-domain EOTF, 3√ó3
 * matrix, and OETF chain as Color::convert(), with transfer functions
 * evaluated via pre-computed LUTs.  Maximum deviation: **¬±2 LSB** for
 * 8-bit conversions.
 *
 * @par Fast path vs scalar pipeline
 * Fast paths use integer BT.709/601/2020 arithmetic which intentionally
 * approximates the sRGB‚ÜîRec.709 transfer function difference as
 * negligible.  Maximum deviation from the scalar pipeline: **‚â§35 LSB**
 * near black where the sRGB and Rec.709 linear segments diverge.  For
 * mid-range and highlight values, the deviation is typically ‚â§2 LSB.
 *
 * @par Fast path round-trip
 * RGB ‚Üí YCbCr ‚Üí RGB via fast paths incurs ‚â§3 LSB error for achromatic
 * and saturated colors (integer quantization).  Chroma subsampling
 * (4:2:2, 4:2:0) introduces additional spatial error at sharp color
 * transitions.
 *
 * @par 10-bit accuracy
 * 10-bit fast paths use the same fixed-point structure scaled to the
 * 10-bit range (Y: 64‚Äì940, Cb/Cr: 64‚Äì960).  When the source is
 * upconverted from 8-bit, the combined tolerance is **¬±4 LSB**.
 *
 * @par 12-bit accuracy
 * 12-bit fast paths use fixed-point arithmetic scaled to the 12-bit
 * limited range (Y: 256‚Äì3760, Cb/Cr: 256‚Äì3840, out of 0‚Äì4095).
 * Round-trip (RGBA12 ‚Üí YCbCr12 ‚Üí RGBA12) error is ‚â§3 LSB for
 * achromatic and saturated colors.  Chroma subsampling (4:2:2, 4:2:0)
 * introduces additional spatial error at sharp color transitions.
 *
 * @section csc_config Configuration
 *
 * CSCPipeline accepts a MediaNodeConfig for runtime hints:
 *
 * | Key      | Type   | Default       | Description |
 * |----------|--------|---------------|-------------|
 * | `"Path"` | String | `"optimized"` | `"optimized"` enables SIMD and fast paths. `"scalar"` forces the generic float pipeline with no SIMD. |
 *
 * @code
 * // Force scalar path for debugging / reference comparison
 * MediaNodeConfig cfg;
 * cfg.set(CSCPipeline::KeyPath, "scalar");
 * Image dst = src.convert(PixelDesc::YUV8_422_Rec709, metadata, cfg);
 * @endcode
 *
 * @section csc_threading Thread Safety
 *
 * CSCPipeline is immutable after construction and safe to execute
 * concurrently from multiple threads.  Each thread must provide its
 * own CSCContext for scratch storage.  Image::convert() creates a
 * temporary context internally, so no manual context management is
 * needed for the high-level API.
 *
 * @section csc_extending Adding Custom Fast Paths
 *
 * Register a fast path at static initialization:
 *
 * @code
 * static void myKernel(const void *const *srcPlanes,
 *                      const size_t *srcStrides,
 *                      void *const *dstPlanes,
 *                      const size_t *dstStrides,
 *                      size_t width, CSCContext &ctx) {
 *     // Convert one scanline...
 * }
 *
 * static struct MyRegistrar {
 *     MyRegistrar() {
 *         CSCRegistry::registerFastPath(
 *             PixelDesc::MySourceFormat,
 *             PixelDesc::MyTargetFormat,
 *             myKernel);
 *     }
 * } __myRegistrar;
 * @endcode
 *
 * The pipeline will automatically use the registered kernel when
 * constructing a CSCPipeline for that source/target pair, unless
 * the `"Path"` config is set to `"scalar"`.
 *
 * @section csc_testing Test Strategy
 *
 * The CSC test suite validates conversions at multiple levels:
 *
 * - **Level 1**: Color::convert() single-pixel validation (ground truth)
 * - **Level 2**: Scalar pipeline consistency with Color::convert() (¬±2 LSB)
 * - **Level 3**: VideoTestPattern through scalar pipeline vs Color reference
 * - **Level 4**: VideoTestPattern through fast path vs BT.709 integer reference (¬±1 LSB)
 * - **Level 5**: Round-trip accuracy (RGB ‚Üí YCbCr ‚Üí RGB)
 * - **Level 6**: Cross-format consistency (same source ‚Üí multiple YCbCr layouts)
 * - **Level 7**: 10-bit consistency (8-bit upconversion ‚Üí 10-bit YCbCr)
 * - **Level 8**: Range boundaries and edge cases
 * - **Level 9**: Rec.601 / Rec.2020 coefficient validation
 *
 * @see CSCPipeline, CSCContext, CSCRegistry, Image::convert()
 * @see @ref color_science "Color Science" for the underlying color model architecture.
 */
